content:
Creating a website navigation menu using C++ isn't feasible because C++ is not a web development language. Typically, HTML, CSS, and JavaScript are used to create website interfaces, including navigation menus. However, I can guide you on how to create a simple navigation menu using HTML and CSS, which is more appropriate for web development.

Here's an example of how you can create a navigation menu with the options "Home," "About," "Services," and "Contact":

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Navigation Menu</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
        .nav-menu {
            list-style-type: none;
            padding: 0;
            background-color: #333;
        }
        .nav-menu li {
            display: inline;
            margin-right: 10px;
        }
        .nav-menu a {
            text-decoration: none;
            color: white;
            padding: 10px 15px;
            display: inline-block;
        }
        .nav-menu a:hover {
            background-color: #575757;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <ul class="nav-menu">
        <li><a href="#home">Home</a></li>
        <li><a href="#about">About</a></li>
        <li><a href="#services">Services</a></li>
        <li><a href="#contact">Contact</a></li>
    </ul>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:

- **HTML**: This code defines a simple unordered list (`<ul>`) with list items (`<li>`) for each menu option. Each option is wrapped in an anchor (`<a>`) tag to make it a clickable link.

- **CSS**: 
  - The `.nav-menu` class removes default list styles and sets a background color for the navigation bar.
  - Each list item (`li`) is displayed inline to arrange them horizontally.
  - The anchor tags are styled to change their background color when hovered over, providing a visual cue for interactivity.

You can modify the styles as needed to better fit the design of your website. For dynamic behaviors or interaction, you might add JavaScript, but this basic setup provides a static menu structure.
